{"abstract": "Joe Belfiore, the corporate vice president of Microsoft Windows Phone, discusses goals for 2014 and the potential upside of the company\u2019s Nokia deal.", "web_url": "https://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/02/23/q-a-with-joe-belfiore-on-the-future-of-windows-phone/", "snippet": "Joe Belfiore, the corporate vice president of Microsoft Windows Phone, discusses goals for 2014 and the potential upside of the company\u2019s Nokia deal.", "lead_paragraph": "Joe Belfiore is the corporate vice president of Microsoft Windows Phone, and he oversees the software that powers handsets using the company\u2019s operating system. Microsoft is expected to close its $7.2 billion deal to buy the handset and services division of Nokia by the end of March. The acquisition will give Microsoft control of both mobile software and hardware, as it looks to expand its 4 percent market share in global smartphone sales. Mr. Belfiore will play a crucial role in Microsoft\u2019s efforts to take on Apple and the cellphone makers that use Google\u2019s Android operating system. ", "source": "The New York Times", "multimedia": [{"rank": 0, "subtype": "xlarge", "caption": null, "credit": null, "type": "image", "url": "images/2014/02/23/business/23bits-belfiore/23bits-belfiore-articleLarge.jpg", "height": 400, "width": 600, "subType": "xlarge", "crop_name": "articleLarge", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2014/02/23/business/23bits-belfiore/23bits-belfiore-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": 600, "xlargeheight": 400}}, {"rank": 0, "subtype": "jumbo", "caption": null, "credit": null, "type": "image", "url": "images/2014/02/23/business/23bits-belfiore/23bits-belfiore-jumbo.jpg", "height": 682, "width": 1024, "subType": "jumbo", "crop_name": "jumbo", "legacy": {}}, {"rank": 0, "subtype": "superJumbo", "caption": null, "credit": null, "type": "image", "url": "images/2014/02/23/business/23bits-belfiore/23bits-belfiore-superJumbo.jpg", "height": 1365, "width": 2048, "subType": "superJumbo", "crop_nam